author: Brave Concepts
description: Dear shills and Villenuvians, I am sorry to disturb you but the Dune 1984 trailer BY ITSELF has more logic, structure, film making sense and "magic" than the entire 156 minutes of Villainuff\'s Dune. (2021) Just the phrase "he who controls the spice, controls the universe" sums it up. Just the warning of the Guild navigator to the Emperor sums it up. Even Fayd Rautha\'s menace sums it up. (Of course these are all missing in Villainuff\'s Dune) David Lynch had to cram the whole story into 1 SINGLE MOVIE... a 137 minute film... where Villainuff couldn\'t even bother to explain the basic setting, mayor players and background in 156 minutes of HALF of his version. Villeneuve DOES NOT CARE about Dune. He cares about photography and scenic landscapes. Villeneuve sells IMAX CANDY. He DOES NOT care about immersing a new audience into Dune\'s story. Villeneuve isn\'t worth the choam on his cappuccino. His version is worth an IMAX ticket but nothing will linger in your mind. It\'s a PG13 THEME PARK RIDE. Go enjoy it but leave your brains at home.

author: Dzengiz Tafa
description: To put it this way (spoiler free)... Allthough Dune (part one) tried to tell an epic story with beautiful visuals and an interesting music score it yields a very boring result without stakes and no character development. You would expect that in a 2 and a half hour movie that serves as a prologue at least the story is laid out and ends with a climax to keep you interested for part two. Sad to say that the movie doesn\'t even build up to a climax and ends like "whut? This is it?". There is no character development at all which renders an impact of a scene or death of a character emotionless. You couldn\'t care less about what happens. The movie drags on with long dragging scenes that are supported by its epic score. The stakes however are immensly lacking. A scene or event in movies normally lead to repercussions and ripple effects that add meaning to certain scenes. The severe lack of any meaningfullness and impact of key story events throughout left me wondering what else I could have done with my 2 and a half hours. In a movie that I expected me to get blown away only i can only applaud the score and visuals but those arent nearly enough when it does\'t have a moving story, stakes and character development to back it up. What we are left with however is a work of abstract and expermental art where all I wanted was an epic movie experience.

author: Sebt
description: Frank Herbert once said - "I wrote the Dune series because I had this idea that *charismatic leaders* ought to come with a warning label on their forehead: May be dangerous to your health. Charismatic leaders tend to build followings, power structures that tend to be taken by people who are corruptible. Power attracts corruptible. Dune is conceived as a planet that is totally desert, so the water on it is a metaphor of oil here, clean air, potable water itself, a metaphor for these shortages that we are encountering and the story is told in terms of people who are recognizable, but they live in a culture that is somewhat... different." ;)

Also the Atreides weren\'t sent to Arrakis to " pacify " it, it was a poisoned gift and a scheme from the Emperor to counter Leto\'s growing influence. And Leto knew it. Maybe all of this is just for the trailer, to appeal to the masses and cash some money in for the next movie. I hope so. Still I really enjoy the casting, especially Rebcca Ferguson as Lady Jessica. i wonder which Harkonnen Bautista is playing as. Rabban maybe ? And the other bald guy should be the Baron\'s Mentat, Piter de Vries.

author: Kanat Tokhtarbek
description: I really hope for a successful release and rental fees of the film, which will open the way for a new franchise in the form of movie sequels and a series based on the books "Dunes"! The cast is great, except for Zendaya and for the femversion of the planetologist! As for the claims about the choice of an actor for the main role of Timati Shalome, he is the closest to the description in the book - there was actually a 15-year-old teenager there, and he was also frail, if anything! Everyone predicts that the film will fail at the box office, which is very likely, but as for me, if this happens, this film adaptation will receive its recognition from the viewer, as it was with the "Escape from the Shawshank"! Even from the trailers, I can see that the Villeneuve version is better than the David Lynch film adaptation - after all, it\'s fantastic and now with new CGI technologies, Dune had to be removed and finally someone decided to do it! Already for this, Villeneuve has a huge respect! And he knows how to shoot fiction - Blade Runner 2049 and Arrival are very good films, but not for the mass audience who are hooked on trash rides from Disney! I feel that the film will go to me, even if it fails at the box office. I\'m afraid of something else, if it will be successful by turning into a franchise, and sequels will go - when the current popular tolerastic, feminist and LGBT trends will be pushed there!

author: Yeep
description: Afghanistan (2012) I was on a contract in Helmand. While there I read "Dune: House of Atreides". Helmand, and most of Afghanistan for that matter, looks and feels exactly like Arrakis. Frank and Brian Herbert\'s writing by itself makes you feel like you are there. With my relief providing some down time to really focus and read it was surreal every time I opened the book. Imagine being in Helmand, during a small sandstorm, and you feel as though you are reading a book, experiencing a world, from the inside. One of the most beautiful experiences of my life.

And it wasn\'t about resistance to foreign oppression, but about something more fundamental, in which they, the fremen, were poor. It was about water: "Tell me about the waters of your homeworld, Usul." It wasn\'t about the possibility of achieving the self-determination of their people (of being exploited by your own instead of by foreigners), but of creating paradise.

author: Daniel Rodriguez
description: I feel like Timothee Chalamet in Dune will right a lot of wrongs for me comparing his performance to Hayden Christensen in Star Wars Episode II and III. I think Timothee will deliver the performance that we hoped Hayden would have delivered years ago in Star Wars. I know even as a Star Wars fan myself, obviously Dune and Star Wars are two totally different franchises but yet somewhat similar to an extent as Star Wars took a lot of aspects from Dunes Novel. I just think there are similarities between Anakin or even Luke to Paul as characters. Chalamet will have the type of brilliant career I had hoped Hayden would have had years ago but never reached his full potential as an actor. For Sci-fi fans and movie fans in general I think his acting performance will be legendary and unforgettable

author: Andreas
description: Sorry, my English is bad. I stopped counting how often I watched the Trailer since Release. Every frame could be a movie poster - its insane. As a big fan of the source material (books) I am confident the movie is in good hands, which are treating all aspects of the material and themes in a good and humble manner- besides the fact that this movie has to reach new Generations of Fans and must be a hit (so we get Part2 - of the first book). From my point of view I am assured that this movie will be the next "cinematic Event" similiar to Lord of the Rings AND it will satisfy hardcore Dune-Fans (like me) too. As a matter of fact I don¬¥t mind the "muscle or smile" joke, because its a nice Character-Moment and shows (as described in the books) Pauls slim shape. Thats a good way to adress this topic and shows in a second the relationship between charakters. Looking at the director, the cast, the acting, the music, the coloring, the cinematography or what I have seen in the delivered material, what I have heard from people whom have seen approx. 20 Minutes I feel save and respected (as a Dune-Fan). They are doing an outstanding job. This will be groundbreaking in every asspect (and will set the tone and scale for upcoming movies). They created a new fighting technique, because the existing fighting stiles did not fit. Zimmerman (music) created new Instruments to assure new sounds and Impressions. All those details show love and earnestness for Dune.

description: I admit to seeing a remake advertised and saying..here we go again recycling. Really liked soundtrack and fight between Feyd-Rautha and Paul in the original. David Lynch\'s version added an even crazier Harkonnens\' fancy/obsession for human blood and draining of liquids from creatures (such as bugs and cats taped to mice). Understanding while the shaved cat contained the antidote for the poison in Thufir\'s body, this combined with heartplugs goes into the mind and influences of Lynch, not Frank Herbert. Interested in seeing what new additions and twists Denis Villeneuve will include in this new version. So far, it looks like the Fremen are actually hardcore fighters like Herbert stated and not operating tech (weirding modules) that anyone could kill with by merely humming/shouting in it.

author: Monty Vierra
description: Some interesting parallels to the 1984 version in some of the visuals. On the other hand, we can see a far more varied cast here than in the 2000 version. The scene showing Duke Leto in front of all his soldiers, though, shows a sea of white faces. Some people like the new Vladimir Harkonnen, but Ian McNeice was superb in the 2000 version, where he was a remarkable script, including rhyming couplets as Richard III (if memory serves). The music in the 2000 version was outstanding, and I haven\'t heard anything in this trailer that matches it. Finally, there\'s a very strange thing. Apparently WB has launched an attack on a reviewer named Quinn after he gave it a very positive YouTube review! WB is trying to squeeze money out of the review because it included some of the scenes. Hey, WB, this is called "fair use." I\'m content with the 2000 version, so if WB are gonna be jerks, I\'ll watch something else--like the new Foundation series--instead.

author: Dark Hawke
description: Enh. Thirty-seven years later and it doesn\'t look that much better than the 1984 adaptation, if at all. What\'s with the quips? This is a dead-serious world. Frank Herbert didn\'t do quippy dialogue. Still don\'t see what\'s so impressive about this Zendaya chick that she dominates the first third of the trailer. As weird as the personal shields were in the Lynch version, these are worse. And I have new appreciation for Kyle McLachlan\'s Paul Atreides given this new one. But then, we\'re only seeing the first half of the book, so maybe his performance ticks upward when he becomes Usul. Still don\'t know if splitting the book was ballsy or stupid. Are they seriously waiting on the performance of the first half before making the second? They should have filmed both halves, but just broken up the release, a la The Matrix Reloaded  Revolutions, or the original plan for the 1978 Superman movies. I guess we\'ll see what we will see in another three months or so.
title: Enh. Thirty-seven years later and it doesn\'t look that much better than the 1984 adaptation, if at all. What\'s with the quips? This is a dead-serious world. As weird as the personal shields were in the Lynch version, these are worse. And I have new appreciation for Kyle McLachlan\'s Paul Atreides given this new one. But then, we\'re only seeing the first half of the book, so maybe his performance ticks upward when he becomes Usul. Still don\'t know if splitting the book was ballsy or stupid. Are they seriously waiting on the performance of the first half before making the second? They should have filmed both halves, but just broken up the release, a la The Matrix Reloaded  Revolutions, or the original plan for the 1978 Superman movies. I guess we\'ll see what we will see in another three months or so.

author: FifthofAscalante
description: I don\'t like it üò¨. Maybe it just the trailer that looks like generic trash, but not a single line, I think, they said is from the book. Gurney Halleck doesn\'t look or feel like the one in the book. They also seem to have reoriented the grander ideas the way they did in the old Dune film where Paul is a fantastical messiah whereas in the book he was sort engineered to be one and it got out of control. In the first book at least, Fremen don\'t like Arakis where their ancestors have ended up after long prosecution and exile through space, and they dream of terraforming it. This is important for the rest of the story. Here they also added the sort of humour that\'s not in the books, that can be found in Avengers, which is not my thing and I was looking forward to this being something different.

author: Juan Loureiro
description: I do not know how many reviews or reactions I have seen where people express their doubts about whether or not to read the original source, or see the old and disastrous David Lynch film first. My answer is always, and will be, Read-The-Damn-Book! You will be able to appreciate more how extraordinary is the work of Frank Herbert; but, in addition, you can fully appreciate how excellent a filmmaker Denis Villeneuve is. Dune is a difficult book to adapt, Lynch suffered it firsthand. But Denis is a superb filmmaker, who has already tried, more than once, how to adapt a difficult or impossible work. Remember "Arrival"? Try to read "Story of your life" by Ted Chiang and you will see how hard is to bring from there a movie so extraordinary as "Arrival" is; then you understand why Denis is the perfect filmmaker for Dune. I have read the book, Herbert\'s book series (there are six), about 7 times, since I was a teenager, even before Star Wars appeared in the Hollywood firmament. Dune is, in scope and dimension, far superior to all Star Wars ever. Philosophy, ecology, notions about power, governance, imperialism, social issues, leadership and religion, all that and more is in Herbert\'s work. Dune\'s first two books describe Paul\'s journey, from his rising to his crashing downfall. It is a philosophical lesson written in the late 50s, and published in 1965, long before all the big budget series and films that Hollywood has us used to. Star Wars was inspired by Dune and Foundation, but it definitely gravitated to Asimov\'s slight science fiction trend, not Herbert\'s hardcore science fiction, but it owes him in themes and even in geographic details, power structures and even in characters. Dune is the real canonical masterpiece of hardcore science fiction. Period! And Villeneuve is the only director today who can do Herbert justice. And I can guarantee you that, as far as I have been seeing to this day, he is doing him justice.

author: tyuhf sdftvhu
description: Arrest and Sentencing Mr. Yang and his wife Ms. Wang Huijun were arrested on December 3, 2019, while talking to people about Falun Gong at a local market. Although Ms. Wang was released two days later, Mr. Yang was held in Xuanhua Detention Center. The police submitted Mr. Yang‚Äôs case to the procuratorate in April 2020. When his lawyer called prosecutor Cheng Xing on May 7 to inquire about his case, Cheng said that he was planning to indict Mr. Yang and submit his case to the court in two or three days. On September 4, 2020, Mr. Yang was tried in the Xuanhua District Court. He entered a not guilty plea and demanded that the judge play the DVDs confiscated from him. He said he didn‚Äôt violate the law in having Falun Gong informational materials. Mr. Yang‚Äôs daughter also defended him in court. She said, ‚ÄúI have to say something when my father is being treated unjustly.‚Äù She shared how Falun Gong changed her father for the better and brought happiness to her family. She also said that in today\'s society with rapidly declining morality, her father has always taught her to be a kind and upright person. The hearing started at 9:15 a.m. The judge adjourned for a ten-minute break at 11 a.m. When the judge adjourned it a second time around 1:30 p.m., the prosecutor left suddenly without a giving reason, so the judge had to end the hearing. The judge sentenced Mr. Yang to eight years with a 10,000-yuan fine on March 16, 2021. He appealed with the Zhangjiakou City Intermediate Court, which upheld his original sentence on July 19, without having a hearing. He was taken to prison on the same day.

author: Nnamdi Chilo-Offiah
description: This movie is so huge and epic in every way. And it‚Äôs not just shoot em up action. It‚Äôs steeped in deep history  lure with heavy doses of philosophy and mysticism. The source material is so rich and beautiful written that they have a lot of content for back story and even forward stories (like peppering mysteries in the movie that will only be answered in future movies). I honestly think this would have been better as a big budget tv series √† la Game of Thrones or what is planned for Lord of the Rings and Wheel of Time. But now that I think about it, I believe I remember them saying that the Dune franchise will be released in multiple fronts including tv series. Looking at this trailer, I have no doubt that this could have been a billion dollar movie if Covid-19 never happened and it must pain them to have to release this movie during these times. I know Warner Bros has been looking for a big franchise that could front the studio. It should have been the DC universe but that wasn‚Äôt handled properly. No doubt this could have been it, the movie looks beautiful (from the trailer). Maybe it still could, but they will have to handle the Dune franchise very strategically and imaginatively.

author: MicWeb1993
description: Casting is superb. I read the first Dune book in 1964. It\'s been a long wait for a loving treatment of this seminal "world building" science fiction epic (never saw an over 600 page science fiction novel before Dune). The amazing thing is, although there are tech aspects that still seem modern, when you get to the end of it, you realize it is more character, mystic, human potential, martial arts, and Machiavellian driven than typical science fiction of its era which was more about speculative technology. The author even went "steam punk" before the concept had even been born, by taking rayguns and computers off the table, "atomics" off the table (we call them nukes now), and making swords the weapon of choice in personal combat. If this movie had been made in the 70s (with modern budgets and CGI) it would have changed the course of film making - but this film couldn\'t, in most ways, be made until today. SPOILER ALERT: Dune pulled a "Game of Thrones" wtf surprise in the first book, then makes that character THE single most important person in the entire series. So, I hope we get more books in the series converted to movies ASAP.

author: Larry Johnson
description: I first read Dune in 1972, and probably a half-dozen times more since then (I still have the same copy). I had always loved science fiction, but this was the first real space opera that had totally engrossed me. It wasn\'t until after Star Wars in 1977 that I thought about a Dune movie, because up to then filmmaking wasn\'t up to the job technically. The 1984 version was ambitious but disappointing, and I\'ve always been sad for David Lynch, but as movie technology advanced, I\'d hope from time to time that someone would try it again. It appears now that Denis Villeneuve might have made the Dune of my imagination with a cast of A-list actors who look like they were made for their characters. We\'ve waited a long time for this, and the trailers promise something equal to our hopes. And though I\'ll have to drive 200 miles, I think I need to see it at IMAX.

author: K. Edwards
description: Anyone figure out what this trailer is warning us of? Dune is Paul Atreides\', hero\'s journey. His arc is always from just a bit cocky but unsure, and not showing it, almost ready, but deals with it in the moment, then righteous anger and world changing charisma. There is not one scene in this trailer where the lead, Timoth√©e Chalamet, isn\'t taking second to the rest of the cast. I fear this is a classic, "we are going to wedge an attractive young actor into a HUGE role and make him a star." You don\'t make stars. So now the "Official Main Trailer" leads with a proven actress. We don\'t see him until 40 seconds, he gets dissed badly, and vanishes for a while. Why did they delay this a couple weeks? Editors are trying to save a movie... sigh.. Look at the emotion in the eyes of Zendaya changing scene by scene, then his chronic "sad and lost boy eyes" scene after scene. Paul sad to have no muscles Paul sad to be upset about his family Paul sad to have a dagger in his hands Paul sad that is not really able to show anger. This trailer creates too many director / lead questions for me. Glad it is streaming on a service I have. I have been waiting for this for years, but too much fear that someone had a "star maker" agenda vs a make Dune right agenda. The trailer editors had a real problem finding any place where the lead anchors the moment. A) Worst cut trailer B) Visually amazing movie with cutting edge effects, an awesome cast, and a weak lead, because someone\'s mandate was to make him the next...... Hope I am wrong, but this trailer does not say, we have given you Paul as written, as the story demands. We have given you "sad boy" lost in a big movie.

author: Flameboar
description: This trailer is fantastic! Dune 2021 should be a blockbuster. Yesterday, someone from WB claimed a video that Quinn posted on his YouTube channel "Quinn\'s Ideas". Quinn, if you do not know, has for several years been hyping Dune 2021 as one of the biggest movies for decades. Quinn\'s video was full of praise for the Dune trailer as being absolutely amazing. He was praising the actors and actresses in the movie. He was creating positive buzz for the upcoming film in a way that few other people could do. WB was getting the best form of advertising that exists. His extremely high praise will bring many people to the box office to see Dune when it opens. Why would someone from WB claim his video for copyright issues. Whoever at WB made this decision stabbed one of Dune\'s biggest fans in the back yesterday by claiming his video. If you do this sort of thing, you will alienate the fan base that is currently building in large part because of the positive buzz that YouTube creators are producing. Please do not destroy your fan base as it is building. I want to see Dune 2021 be very successful so that there can be more movies to tell more of the Dune sage. Warner Brothers can hurt this movie by alienating the fan base. Please do whatever you can to keep the most ardent Dune fans producing positive hype. An please reverse the claim on Quinn\'s video.

author: Scott Weaver
description: From this preview I do not see that Villeneuve has matched the otherworldly look or sound space of David Lynch\'s Dune (1984). When I see it perhaps it will become more clear why he wanted to \'remake\' this film. Perhaps it adheres more closely to the book? Thinking back to Blade Runner 2049 it had wonderful visuals, but neither those or the script rose to the level of the original Ridley Scott film. I notice the co-writer of this new Dune wrote the scripts to some disappointing movies: Prometheus, and The Mummy (2017), and several more. It\'s a shame to remake a powerful film 20 years later and not at least equal it. Example: Ben Hur (2016)

author: Turkish4224
description: I am a huge fan of the book, read it at least 5 times so far. Have seen the Lynch version repeatedly. After Arrival I have been looking forward to this project becoming reality. Yet, after this trailer I am afraid of two things. First that the music will be formulaic - prisoner to Zimmer\'s composition formulas and Hollywood\'s preconceived ideas about how "sand" and "exotic" should sound - all that oriental wailing vocals. Second, and more serious, I am afraid that, for the sake of commercial targets and the incessant money making formulas that are used these days in blockbusters, (forced usage of humor at paced intervals being one) Villneuve will not convey the tone of the book right. Dune is rather bleak and philosophical, and Dune\'s worlds and people are eerie, and intense. I really hope the movie will not be turned into a mindless joke fest - just because the public is used to that from MCU or sorts. Arrival is wonderful and subtle and strange and artistic and aesthetically gorgeous. Please Villneuve, aim for that.

author: Peter A
description: JESUS LOVES YOU!!! He loves you so much that He hung on a cross and took upon Himself all the sins you would ever commit, the question now is ‚ÄúDo you love Him‚Äù? How do you genuinely show your love to someone? What is the greatest showing of love? The answer is sacrifice and then time. Christ Jesus paid the cost for us, through His sacrifice on the cross that we may live a life of health, deliverance and prosperity. What is it that you lose in spending time with Him, thanking Him for the privilege of seeing another day, and by reading His word ‚ÄúThe Bible‚Äù.......nothing. He offers you the gift of eternal life through having a relationship with Him, and partaking in this relationship immensely benefits you . He protects, guides, provides, heals, delivers, prospers, blesses you, and so much more. A true, authentic relationship involves communication on both sides. Christ Jesus is often taken for granted, many don‚Äôt give Him the slightest of acknowledgement, regardless He is still merciful and loving. Seek Him, acknowledge you‚Äôre a sinner, lost without Him and destined for destruction, REPENT, REPENT, REPENT, believe in your heart wholeheartedly what He did for you on that cross and His resurrection. Confess with your mouth that He is Lord, and you‚Äôve taken your first steps on that straight and narrow path to eternity in heaven with Him. And in this process your life will never remain the same, He will give you the Holy Spirit and grace, which will transform you and enable you to overcome sin, temptations and addiction and live a life that shows your love for Him. Slip ups happen, no one is perfect, but through asking for forgiveness and by His grace it will occur less and less. And you will enjoy pleasing Him and living a righteous life. You have everything to gain in Christ Jesus. Have a blessed day!

author: Applecrow
description: For those new to Dune and curious, start with Dune and be aware that the first 3 are a loose trilogy, book 4 is a bridge to what was going to be a second trilogy, and Frank died after book 6. The other filmed adaptations have their ups and downs and are well worth watching. IF you decide to read any of Brian\'s books please be well aware that they are nowhere near the complexity and they are widely rejected as canon, especially when they start to say Frank\'s books were wrong. There are several stories about Brian using his father\'s notes to finish the books but we don\'t know what those notes contain and even then they change major plotlines to make characters they introduced critical to the wrapup.

author: EternalRoman
description: Decrepit Raspy voice high floating pale skin Baron...why do they still mess up that character so much? I can go with everything else, but the 80s and this version of the Harkonnens are so wrong in their clear description of the character (s) from the book. In the novel the Baron has a Basso (profundo) voice, is grossly fat with anti gravity suspensors to allow him to float a few inches off the ground, cherub locked red hair, baby looking fat face with puffed lips and a charming personality that hides a sadistic, and amazingly evil, perverted genius mind...Baron Vladimir Harkonnen a pure image of overindulgence in all pleasures and tastes seen in the noble castes, smh...the closest that the character was done correctly was in 2000 with SciFi\'s DUNE miniseries and THE CHILDREN OF DUNE. This movie looks fine, but again, why is it so hard to make the Harkonnens right? At least Glossu Rabban by Dave Bautipsta looks somewhat ok, but still not right.

author: WhyMonkey
description: So disappointed. I hope I am badly mistaken, or the trailer poorly represents the actual film, but this is silliest, most boring, teen-age millennial version of Dune I have ever seen. I know David Lynch strayed far far away from the book but at least his movie was unique and entertaining. This version seems to stay closer to the original story but at the same time miss every other mark. Casting, acting and music all forgettable from what I see so far. Sorry to be a downer, but I love these books, and unlike most, have actually read all six of them. This story deserves better.

author: LironMtnRanch
description: Interesting, maybe breaking the movie into 2 parts will make for a better adaption. Story time: In ~1983 I went to Worldcon in Anaheim Ca. One of the most anticipated events was the world premiere of footage from *Dune* with a QA from (the director? Don\'t remember tbh). That theater was filled to standing room only 20 minutes before showtime. When the footage started, this usher in the back of the house kept opening a door to the bright sunny outside, flooding the already rather dim screen with light. The crowd shouted in unison like a switch was turned on the first time this happened. The third time he did it, I swear it was the closest I\'ve ever been to a mob ready to straight up MURDER a person with their bare hands.

author: Javier Armijo
description: With "Dune" as an example, Warner Bros. is showing us that they are brave enough to take heavy risks. Therefore, I think that there is hope to see in this very lifetime a wonderful production of the magnificent and unique epic of Indian Subcontinent; The Mahabharata. Certainly, a fair covering of this work will move millions of people on the whole planet. Then, the western world will discover an ancient masterpiece of the universal literature. Action, intrigue, romance and more action, life teachings, adorables characters... everything is there, even polyandry. Here where I live, there is a saying "The hope is the last thing to lose". So, come on Warner Bros., we can wait 10 or 20 years more, but, bring it to the life. The world deserves it. I think that only you, or maybe HBO or Netflix as a TV series, could do it well. People here, What do you think about it?

author: Benri
description: Looks gorgeous, and I\'ll definitely see it. But it\'ll bomb, and that\'s because Timothee Chalamet is an irritating, insufferable personality who has no proven box office draw. If you wanted this to be a success, there are plenty of young actors (albeit less skilled ones) who would\'ve been a draw in a way Timmy won\'t be. Momoa and Bautista are great "bro" superstars but the dopes who want to see wrestlers as movie stars aren\'t going to go see an arthouse boondoggle. Zendaya hasn\'t proven that she has star power on her own, and while Oscar Isaac is probably the most underappreciated actor of his generation, he\'s not going to put butts in seats either. If this clears $400 mil worldwide I\'ll be astounded. And if Part II isn\'t released direct to HBO Max, I\'ll be even MORE astounded. But again, Villenueve is a genius and it looks beautiful and I can\'t wait to watch it.
